<ns3449:section xmlns:ns3449="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.technologies.java.j2se.security.securityModels.java2SecurityModel">
    
    
    <ns3450:title xmlns:ns3450="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Java 2 Security Model</ns3450:title>

<ns3451:para xmlns:ns3451="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">In Java 2 (<ns3452:abbrev xmlns:ns3452="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">i.e.</ns3452:abbrev> from JDK version 1.2 onwards) a <ns3453:emphasis xmlns:ns3453="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">security policy</ns3453:emphasis> can
be assigned to all code, irrespective of whether it was loaded locally or 
remotely. The security policy specifies a set of <ns3454:emphasis xmlns:ns3454="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">permissions</ns3454:emphasis> for code
from various signers or locations. These permissions can be can be configured
by a user or system administrator. </ns3451:para>

<ns3455:para xmlns:ns3455="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Each permission specifies a permitted access to a particular resource. For 
example, a permission could specify 
  <ns3456:itemizedlist xmlns:ns3456="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
  <ns3457:listitem xmlns:ns3457="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns3458:para xmlns:ns3458="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Read and/or write access to a file or directory.</ns3458:para></ns3457:listitem>
  <ns3459:listitem xmlns:ns3459="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns3460:para xmlns:ns3460="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Connect access to a specified host and port.</ns3460:para></ns3459:listitem>
  </ns3456:itemizedlist>
</ns3455:para>

<ns3461:para xmlns:ns3461="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">The Java run-time environment organizes code into <ns3462:emphasis xmlns:ns3462="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">security domains</ns3462:emphasis>.
Each security domain controls the access of a set of classes whose instances
are granted the same set of permissions.</ns3461:para>
</ns3449:section>